item.title: Semana 1 (Semestre 3)
item.description:
The lj/cut/dipole/cut potential is used with a cutoff of 20. The parameters for the pair coefficients (pair_coeff) seem reasonable, but the attractive part of the Lennard-Jones potential might be too strong, causing particles to collapse into a single sphere.
Modifcation: Adjusted the pair coefficients to reduce the attractive forces. For example, increase the epsilon parameter (e.g., pair_coeff 1 1 0.01 2.49451641079295 2.8 20) to make the repulsive part stronger.


Modification: So the problem of collapsing, like the wave function, may be because of the bond energy, which can be too strong so therefore, I decreased it and also reduced the distance of the bond, this seemed to help, now the Ratchet compacts just a little, to reach the appropriate distance.


Apparently, it still breaks after a time, upon revision of the simulation, one magnetic colloid approach very fast to the Ratchet, comes very close and therefore creates and instability and the particle goes flying.

def compute_com(timesteps): com_results = {} for timestep, positions in timesteps.items(): com_x = np.mean(positions[:, 0]) com_y = np.mean(positions[:, 1]) com_results[timestep] = (com_x, com_y) return com_results
def convert_to_polar(timesteps, com_results): polar_results = {} for timestep, positions in timesteps.items(): com_x, com_y = com_results[timestep] polar_coords = [] for x, y in positions: r = np.sqrt((x - com_x) ** 2 + (y - com_y) ** 2) theta = np.arctan2(y - com_y, x - com_x) #* 180 / np.pi if theta < 0: theta = 2 * np.pi + theta polar_coords.append((r, theta)) polar_results[timestep] = np.array(polar_coords) return polar_results
def compute_angular_velocity(polar_results, timesteps): angular_velocities = {} sorted_timesteps = sorted(timesteps.keys()) for i in range(len(sorted_timesteps) - 1): t1, t2 = sorted_timesteps[i], sorted_timesteps[i + 1] delta_t = (t2 - t1) * 10 theta_t1 = polar_results[t1][:, 1] theta_t2 = polar_results[t2][:, 1] delta_theta = np.unwrap(theta_t2 - theta_t1) omega = delta_theta / delta_t mean_omega = np.mean(omega) angular_velocities[t2] = (omega, mean_omega) return angular_velocities

item.title: Semana 12 (Semestre 2)
item.description:
For this week, the task was to be able to achieve that the simulation magcolloids works at the stablished frequency and angle, and of course at the correct magnetic field. In the paper it says the angle is around 30, and the magnetic field is 7.2 mT, and the only thing that changed was the frequency, starting with 0Hz and 3Hz.
(I did not know how to copy the output)
What we can see at 0Hz is that the particles are attaching to each other and present a brownian motion.
At 6Hz the particles seem to behave like crazy, it can be seen a lot of movement in every direction too fast.

My first attempt to represent a ratchet with lammps was using figures from the same lammps, and achieve something like this.
It seemed like an amazing idea, until I could not find if it was possible to make, in this case, the cross being moved by the particles, because it is a function that makes the cross spin, but not pretty sure if worked with the forces of the particles.

So, even though I did not want to be using these things, I did not have other choice, becuase I felt it very difficult to be manpulating too many particles and make them with the correct bonds, and angles and dihedrals.
So to begin with, we want to start the particles in a circle form, which it was achieved.

But, to be honest I am very lazy, and tried to automate it with python, to make the bonds and angles, and dihedrals with their respective particles, and I think I achieved it.

item.title: Semana 13 (Semestre 2)
item.description:
The basis vectors (or lattice vectors) are the fundamental building blocks used to generate the entire crystal lattice by translation. These vectors define the geometry of the unit cell, and by repeating the unit cell across space, you form the overall lattice structure.
In the hexagonal lattice, the basis vectors determine the relative positions of atoms in the unit cell. These vectors are used to place atoms and generate the positions of all atoms in the simulation box.

In a 2D hexagonal lattice (also called honeycomb or graphene-like lattice), the two primary basis vectors are:
— This points along the x-axis.
— This points in a diagonal direction, defining the hexagonal arrangement in the x-y plane.
The third basis vector is optional in a 2D lattice but becomes important in 3D:
— This points along the z-axis, defining the third dimension (if needed, for 3D cases).

The basis vectors are used to define how atoms are arranged withing a unit cell, and then, by translating them across the lattice, generate the full structure.
In the code, the basis vectors , , and define how the atoms are spaced in the simulation box. By scaling these vectors and using integer multiples of them, it is possible to generate all atomic positions in the lattice.
# Define lattice parameters a = 1.0 # Lattice constant (defines the size of the unit cell) # Base vectors for hexagonal lattice a1 = np.array([a, 0, 0]) # First basis vector along x-axis a2 = np.array([a / 2, np.sqrt(3) / 2 * a, 0]) # Second basis vector in the x-y plane a3 = np.array([0, 0, a]) # Third basis vector along z-axis (for 3D, if needed)

Once the basis vectors are defined, the atomic positions are generated by applying integer multiples of the basis vectors to create a grid of atoms in the lattice.
# Create arrays for atomic positions positions = [] for i in range(nx): # Loop over x-direction unit cells for j in range(ny): # Loop over y-direction unit cells for k in range(nz): # Loop over z-direction unit cells (optional for 3D) # Calculate the atomic position for this cell pos = i * a1 + j * a2 + k * a3 positions.append(pos)
The i, j, and k loops represent the integer multiples that scale the basis vectors, this creates a grid of atoms where each atom is placed according to its combination of integer multiples of the basis vectors.



First of all, we want to start with a easy shape, that is a circle, which is given by:
And can be generated in with the following code:
# Generate atom coordinates atoms = [] for i in range(N): x = R * np.cos(2 * np.pi * i / N) y = R * np.sin(2 * np.pi * i / N) atoms.append([i+1, 1, 1, round(x, 2), round(y, 2), z_coord])


To add a sawtooth shape to the circle and crete a ratchet-like appearance, we can modify the radial distance R periodically as we go around the circle. This will make the atoms follow a "sawtooth" pattern along the radius.
For this we need to define the frequency and amplitude of the sawtooth function, controlling the number of peaks and the "depth" of each peak in the ratchet shape.
Modifying the code we end up with:
atoms = [] for i in range(N): # Modulate the radius with a sawtooth pattern sawtooth_mod = saw_amp * (i % (N // saw_freq)) / (N // saw_freq) R_mod = R + sawtooth_mod - (saw_amp / 2) # Offset to center sawtooth x = R_mod * np.cos(2 * np.pi * i / N) y = R_mod * np.sin(2 * np.pi * i / N) atoms.append([i+1, 1, 1, round(x, 2), round(y, 2), z_coord])


Having the shape and the lattice, we can possibly make that all the particles that are outside the shape, are removed and the ones that are inside kept.
atoms = [] for i in range(N): # Modulate the radius with a sawtooth pattern sawtooth_mod = saw_amp * (i % (N // saw_freq)) / (N // saw_freq) R_mod = R + sawtooth_mod - (saw_amp / 2) # Offset to center sawtooth x = R_mod * np.cos(2 * np.pi * i / N) y = R_mod * np.sin(2 * np.pi * i / N) atoms.append([i+1, 1, 1, round(x, 2), round(y, 2), z_coord])
To start, I wanted to be able to make the lattice be filtered by a mere circle, at the beginning the shape was just of a triangle, and I noticed it was because of the lattice moving just in the positive direction in x and y, and the circle was in the center, so I modified the lattice to move in all directions, and obtained the following:

for i in range(-nx, nx): # Extending in both positive and negative x directions for j in range(-ny, ny): # Extending in both positive and negative y directions for k in range(nz): # Calculate the atomic position for this cell pos = i * a1 + j * a2 + k * a3 # Check if position is within the circle in the xy plane distance_from_center = np.linalg.norm(pos[:2] - center[:2]) if distance_from_center <= radius: positions.append(pos)

item.title: Semana 14 (Semestre 2)
item.description:
The radius is modulated with a sawtooth pattern as a function of angle. This creates a ratchet-like shape for the boundary.
For each lattice point, we calculate the distance from the center and compare it to the modulated radius (R_mod) at the angle corresponding to the point.
# Center of the circle center = np.array([0.0, 0.0, 0.0]) # Create arrays for atomic positions positions = [] for i in range(-nx, nx): # Extending in both positive and negative x directions for j in range(-ny, ny): # Extending in both positive and negative y directions for k in range(nz): # Calculate the atomic position for this cell pos = i * a1 + j * a2 + k * a3 # Calculate angle of the current lattice point angle = np.arctan2(pos[1], pos[0]) if angle < 0: angle += 2 * np.pi # Normalize angle to [0, 2π] # Calculate the sawtooth-modulated radius for this angle sawtooth_mod = saw_amp * ((angle * N / (2 * np.pi)) % (N // saw_freq)) / (N // saw_freq) R_mod = radius + sawtooth_mod - (saw_amp / 2) # Offset to center sawtooth # Check if position is within the sawtooth-modulated boundary distance_from_center = np.linalg.norm(pos[:2] - center[:2]) if distance_from_center <= R_mod: positions.append(pos) # Convert list to numpy array for easier manipulation positions = np.array(positions)

Once obtained the shape, wee need to make the bonds with the help of Dr. Antonio, we achieved the following example.

tri = spa.Delaunay(positions[:,0:2]) weird_neighbor = tri.vertex_neighbor_vertices indptr = weird_neighbor[0] indices = weird_neighbor[1] k = 2 indices[indptr[k]:indptr[k+1]] neigh_list = [] for i in range(len(positions)): neighbors = indices[indptr[i]:indptr[i+1]] for n in neighbors: if i<n: neigh_list.append([i, n]) neighs = np.array(neigh_list)
So applying this into the filtered lattice, we obtained an abomination,

This was because dealunay method does not have a way to determine which atom has to reach, or where are the limits of the figure, therefore I though about a cuttof:
from scipy.spatial import Delaunay # Perform Delaunay triangulation in 2D (x, y) tri = Delaunay(positions[:, :2]) # Only use x and y # Define a maximum distance for filtering bonds max_distance = a * 1.1 # Create bonds by filtering Delaunay edges based on distance bonds = [] for simplex in tri.simplices: for i in range(3): atom1, atom2 = simplex[i], simplex[(i+1)%3] dist = np.linalg.norm(positions[atom1] - positions[atom2]) if dist <= max_distance: bonds.append((atom1+1, atom2+1)) # Add bond
and reducing the distance between atoms, we obtained a better form and bonds.


I do not posses a video of the simulation, but you can trust that it was no good, with just bonds, because the particles collapses, therefore the addition of angles is necessary.



Neighbors Dictionary: Each atom's list of bonded atoms is stored in a dictionary. For example, if atom 1 is bonded to atoms 2 and 3, neighbors[1] would contain {2, 3}.

Angle Generation: For each atom, combinations of pairs of neighbors are formed to create angles. If atom A has neighbors B and C, then the angle (B,A,C) is created.
Avoiding Duplicates: By sorting the triplet (B,A,C), we ensure that the order of B and C doesn’t affect uniqueness. Adding the triplet to a set automatically avoids duplicates.
neighbors = defaultdict(set) for atom1, atom2 in bonds: neighbors[atom1].add(atom2) neighbors[atom2].add(atom1) angles = set() for atom in neighbors: neighbor_list = list(neighbors[atom]) for i in range(len(neighbor_list)): for j in range(i + 1, len(neighbor_list)): # Create an angle (B, A, C) without duplicate ordering B, A, C = neighbor_list[i], atom, neighbor_list[j] angle = tuple(sorted([B, A, C])) # Sort to avoid duplicates angles.add(angle) # Using a set to keep only unique angles

Maybe I can make sure of the particles that conform an angle, since the triangles are equilateral and therefore the angle is equal or around 60°.

item.title: Semana 15 (Semestre 2)
item.description:
Apparently the function initial_setup is the one in charge of positioning the particles for magcolloids, and we want to merge the ratchet-like particles with these ones.
Parameters

n_of_particles: Desired number of particles.
packing: Packing fraction, defining how densely the particles are arranged.
height: Height of the 3D region containing the particles (assumes particles are constrained in 2D within this height).
radius: Radius of each particle.
Logic
1. Calculate the edge length for square particle arrangement:
part_in_edge calculates the side length (number of particles per edge) of a square grid that can accommodate n_of_particles.
The number of particles is then adjusted to be a perfect square (part_in_edge^2), potentially modifying the particle count.
2. Define region dimensions based on packing density:
area_particle calculates the total area that particles occupy, assuming they are circular.
area_region uses the packing fraction to determine the area of the entire confining region.
length_region is then derived as the square root of area_region, giving the side length of a square enclosing the particles.
3. Calculate particle separation:
part_separation is the distance between particle centers in the grid.
4. Generate initial positions for particles:
Using np.linspace, the x and y positions for particles are spaced uniformly across length_region.
np.meshgrid forms a 2D grid of coordinates.
initial_positions stores these coordinates in a flat array, with Z set to zero, assuming particles are in a 2D plane.
5. Validate packing constraints:
If part_separation < 2 * radius, particles would overlap, so the function raises a ValueError.

import numpy as np def initial_setup(n_of_particles, packing=0.3, height=4, radius=1.4, sawtooth_positions=None): """ Returns initial particle positions confined to a region without overlapping with positions in sawtooth_positions. The particles are arranged in a square grid to maximize separation. """ part_in_edge = int(np.round(np.sqrt(n_of_particles))) n_of_particles = part_in_edge**2 area_particle = n_of_particles * radius**2 * np.pi area_region = area_particle / packing length_region = np.sqrt(area_region) part_separation = length_region / part_in_edge x_loc = np.linspace( -length_region/2 + part_separation/2, length_region/2 - part_separation/2, part_in_edge) y_loc = np.linspace( -length_region/2 + part_separation/2, length_region/2 - part_separation/2, part_in_edge) [X, Y] = np.meshgrid(x_loc, y_loc) Z = np.zeros(np.shape(X)) initial_positions = [] for x, y, z in zip(X.flatten(), Y.flatten(), Z.flatten()): pos = np.array([x, y, z]) # Check distance to sawtooth-modulated positions if sawtooth_positions is not None: min_distance = np.min(np.linalg.norm(sawtooth_positions[:, :2] - pos[:2], axis=1)) if min_distance < 2 * radius: continue # Skip this position if it’s too close to the sawtooth boundary particles initial_positions.append(pos) # Convert to array and raise ValueError if packing is too high initial_positions = np.array(initial_positions) if part_separation < 2 * radius: raise ValueError("packing is too high") region = [np.round(length_region), np.round(length_region), height] return region, initial_positions

sawtooth_positions parameter:
Accepts a list or array of positions from the ratchet function.
Distance Check:
For each particle position (pos) in the grid, calculates the minimum distance to all sawtooth_positions using np.linalg.norm.
If this minimum distance is less than 2 * radius, the particle is skipped to avoid overlap.
Output:
The function returns region and initial_positions, where initial_positions excludes particles overlapping with sawtooth-modulated positions.

item.title: Semana 16 (Semestre 2)
item.description:
New Functionality:
Implemented the initial_setup function to generate initial positions for particles. Key features include:
Overlap Avoidance: Ensures particles do not overlap with each other or with the predefined sawtooth boundary positions.
Dynamic Adaptability: Automatically adjusts the number of particles based on input parameters to meet packing and spatial constraints.
Handling Constraints:
Integrated a check to enforce a minimum distance between generated particles and the sawtooth-modulated boundary particles.


Successfully generated particle distributions within the confined region for test cases of varying particle numbers, radii, and packing densities.
Confirmed robustness of the function for different boundary configurations, ensuring compatibility with the sawtooth-modulated ratchet geometry.

def initial_setup(n_of_particles, packing=0.3, height=4, radius=1.4, sawtooth_positions=None): """ Returns initial particle positions confined to a region without overlapping with positions in sawtooth_positions. The particles are arranged in a square grid to maximize separation. """ part_in_edge = int(np.round(np.sqrt(n_of_particles))) n_of_particles = part_in_edge**2 area_particle = n_of_particles * radius**2 * np.pi area_region = area_particle / packing length_region = np.sqrt(area_region) part_separation = length_region / part_in_edge x_loc = np.linspace( -length_region/2 + part_separation/2, length_region/2 - part_separation/2, part_in_edge) y_loc = np.linspace( -length_region/2 + part_separation/2, length_region/2 - part_separation/2, part_in_edge) [X, Y] = np.meshgrid(x_loc, y_loc) Z = np.zeros(np.shape(X)) initial_positions = [] for x, y, z in zip(X.flatten(), Y.flatten(), Z.flatten()): pos = np.array([x, y, z]) # Check distance to sawtooth-modulated positions if sawtooth_positions is not None: min_distance = np.min(np.linalg.norm(sawtooth_positions[:, :2] - pos[:2], axis=1)) if min_distance < 1.5 * radius: continue # Skip this position if it’s too close to the sawtooth boundary particles initial_positions.append(pos) # Convert to array and raise ValueError if packing is too high initial_positions = np.array(initial_positions) if part_separation < 2 * radius: raise ValueError("packing is too high") region = [np.round(length_region), np.round(length_region), height] return region, initial_positions
It was successfully implemented for magcolloids, and now the next step is to make a simulation in lammps.

As we can see, it checks out with the graph, but the only thing left is to merge the ratchet and the magnetic colloids.

According to Lammps:
The read_data command can be used multiple times with the same or different data files to build up a complex system from components contained in individual data files.*


The simulation box is created based on the first data file unless create_box is used beforehand.
The add keyword can't be used when initializing the system.
Subsequent calls:
The add keyword is used to specify how new atoms, bonds, etc., are incorporated.
IDs, types, and coordinates can be offset or shifted using the provided keywords.


append:
Adds atoms with new IDs shifted by the current max ID.
Example: If the largest atom ID is 1000, the new IDs start at 1001. (Or that is what I understood)

IDoffset:
Adds a fixed offset to all IDs.
Example: If IDoffset = 2000, an atom with ID 1 in the new data file becomes ID 2001. (Maybe this will help)

merge:
Directly incorporates new atoms without modifying IDs. It is important to ensure no duplicate IDs exist.


Orthogonal boxes:
The box size grows to accommodate new atoms if needed.
It is important to ensure bonded atoms across periodic boundaries don't separate due to box growth.
Triclinic boxes:
Subsequent data files must match the box type and tilts from the first file.


Use of extra keywords:
If we know additional types (atoms, bonds, etc.) will be added, then we should specify them during the first read_data call or with create_box.
Example: If the first file uses only one atom type, and the second uses two new types, use:
read_data file1.data extra/atom/types 2

The input file given from magcolloids is used,to simply merge the ratchet data file. The proposed adjustments are the following.

Reads hexagonal_lattice.data.
Reserves space for additional atom and bond types using extra.
Appends test.lmpdatawith theadd` keyword.
Uses offset to shift atom types to avoid conflicts.
Obtaining something like this
### ---preamble--- ### log ./test.log units micro atom_style hybrid ellipsoid paramagnet bond boundary p p f neighbor 4.0 bin neigh_modify every 1 delay 1 check yes pair_style hybrid lj/cut/dipole/cut 1 20 bond_style biharmonic ### ---Create Particles and Region--- ### # First data file read_data ./hexagonal_lattice.data extra/atom/types 1 extra/bond/types 1 # Second data file read_data ./test.lmpdata add append offset 1 0 0 0 0 group Atoms type 1 mass * 1 group Atoms_1 type 1 ### ---Variables--- ### ## magnetic field variable Bmag atom 1.9428613454361806e-05 variable freq atom 6e-06 variable theta atom 0.518362787842
And with that adjustment an error was obtained, that states the following:
ERROR: Incorrect atom format in data file (../atom.cpp:883)
Last command: read_data ./hexagonal_lattice.data extra/atom/types 1 extra/bond/types 1
But, it is important to notice that the hexagonal_lattice.data file has nothing to do by itself, because we obtained the following simulation.


Key change
bond_style hybrid: to have bihormonic and harmonic styles
bond_style harmonic biharmonic
And according to documentation, this is the way to specify the bond we are using
Bond Coeffs 1 harmonic 80.0 1.2 2 fene 30.0 1.5 1.0 1.0 ...
And even with that change we obtained the same error.
ERROR: Incorrect atom format in data file (../atom.cpp:883)
Last command: read_data ./hexagonal_lattice.data extra/atom/types 1 extra/bond/types 1
The problem could be that, since the atom types were established at the beginning of the input file, therefore the data file is expected to have the same parameters as the magnetic colloids.

### ---preamble--- ### log ./test.log units micro #atom_style hybrid ellipsoid paramagnet bond boundary p p f neighbor 4.0 bin neigh_modify every 1 delay 1 check yes pair_style hybrid lj/cut/dipole/cut 1 20 #bond_style hybrid harmonic biharmonic ### ---Create Particles and Region--- ### # First data file atom_style bond bond_style harmonic read_data ./hexagonal_lattice.data extra/atom/types 1 extra/bond/types 1 # Second data file atom_style hybrid ellipsoid paramagnet bond atom_style biharmonic read_data ./test.lmpdata add append offset 1 0 0 0 0 #read_data ./test.lmpdata group Atoms type 1 mass * 1 group Atoms_1 type 1
In this approach, we define the atom and bond style before each read data, that way we ensure each file does not have any problems with the types. And after that we obtain the following error.
==ERROR: Atom_style command after simulation box is defined (../input.cpp:1426)
Last command: atom_style hybrid ellipsoid paramagnet bond ==
And this is because, the first data file is the one in charge of defining the box dimensions. And we need to make sure the box is big enough. So here are 2 options, we make the magcolloids data file is in charge of the box, or we change the lattice file.
For now, we can make the lattice file to be in charge.
And apparently that was not the error. It was because, the atom_style, indeed as the error says, is after a create box. So the overwriting approach was no good. We need to make sure that the atom style is in one line.

Fill the hexagonal lattice data file missing parameters with 0s. And that did not do the trick either.

item.title: Semana 18 (Semestre 2)
item.description:
So far I think I've been working blindfoled, but I did something that at least make the whole simulation finish. Before, the simulations had an error stating that there were lost atoms. And after changing so many numbers, I realized something, there was a multiplied fix ID number


And after changing this number, the simulation finished.

Al disminuar la variable Bmag de1.9428613454361806e-05 a 1.9428613454361806e-06, y dejando la simulación corrió por más tiempo, además, para esta simulación, tuve que desactivar el movimiento browniano para el Rathcet, y solo dejarlo para las particulas magnéticas.
Cabe destacar que para esta simulación, fix set_dipole fue utilizado con normalidad.
Pero se rompe al llegar al paso 7700

Pero al volver a activar brownian dynamics, la simulación únicamente llega a 7600, y de igual manera el ratchet sufre mucha deformación. Parece ser que las fluctuaciones son muy fuertes, y el ratchet debe ser reforzado de alguna forma, esta siendo agregandole una capa más, o agregando angulos entre enlaces.

Para esta nueva versión, se intentará acomodar las partículas en forma de tetrahedro, para verificar si esto reduce las fluctuaciones térmicas.

Conociendo las distancias del centro del cubo a cada arista, podemos determinar los vectores base del sistema.
Podemos observar que va a ser necesario una condición que determine en que lugar del cubo estamos, por que podemos observar que en el centro de este, únicamente hay 1 partícula.
Después de modificar el código de las posiciones iniciales, por este
# Define lattice parameters a = 0.5 # Lattice constant radius = 10.0 # Average radius of the ratchet saw_amp = 4.0 # Amplitude of the sawtooth modulation saw_freq = 4 # Frequency of the sawtooth pattern (number of teeth) N = 1000 # Number of points for the ratchet boundary Kb = 5 #Bond energy coefficient ### For this it will be always 3D a1 = np.array([a, 0, 0]) ##x vector a2 = np.array([0, a, 0]) ##y vector a3 = np.array([0, 0, a]) ##z vector a4 = np.array([a/2, a/2, a/2]) # Number of unit cells in each direction, centered around the origin nx, ny, nz = 3, 1, 1 # Center of the circle center = np.array([0.0, 0.0, 0.0]) positions = [] limx, limy, limz = range(nx), range(ny), range(nz) if nx < 2: limx = range(nx + 1) if ny < 2: limy = range(ny + 1) if nz < 2: limz = range(nz + 1) for i in limx: for j in limy: for k in limz: pos = i * a1 + j * a2 + k * a3 positions.append(pos) if k > 0 and j > 0 and i > 0: positions.append([i * a/2, j * a/2, k * a/2]) positions = np.array(positions)
se obtuvo la siguiente triangulación.


El código anterior tenía problemas al posicionar las partículas centrales si el sistema crecía, así que tuve una epifania en donde conte la solución, la cuál es esta:
limx, limy, limz = range(-nx + 1, nx), range(-ny + 1, ny), range(nz) if nx < 2: limx = range(-nx, nx + 1) if ny < 2: limy = range(-ny, ny + 1) if nz < 2: limz = range(nz + 1) # Loop through lattice and add particles for i in limx: for j in limy: for k in limz: pos = i * a1 + j * a2 + k * a3 positions.append(pos) if i < max(limx): if j < max(limy): if k < max(limz): pos = pos + reference positions.append(pos)

Como podemos ver, a diferencia de una sola capa, este presenta menos fluctuaciones entre las particulas, y solo muestra rotación en todo el cuerpo.



Al correr la simulación integrando ambos data files, se pierden atomos en el primer momento, no permitiendo que haya un video, pero al quitar el fix de brownian dynamics, esta si funciona. Y como se espera, no hay interacción alguna. Y al agregar brownian dynamics unicamente a los coloides, la simulación logra correr durante el tiempo establecido, que son 40,000 no sé qué.

Cabe destacar que No tenian el fix set dipole, una vez agregado, la simulación se rompe al tiempo 11,300 no sé qué de 40,000 no sé qué.

item.title: Semana 19 (Semestre 2)
item.description:
Configuración del sistema:
Las partículas paramagnéticas de 4.5 μm están confinadas en dos dimensiones y forman un cristal triangular no compacto debido a la repulsión magnética inducida por un campo magnético perpendicular.
Las bacterias (E. coli con proteorrodopsina) inducen movimiento activo en las partículas mediante interacciones estocásticas. Su actividad se controla con luz verde, ajustando la velocidad de nado.
Control de los parámetros del sistema:
Temperatura efectiva global:
Se introduce una temperatura adimensional (T∗) que combina el efecto de la difusión térmica y activa, ajustable mediante el campo magnético y la intensidad de luz.
La expresión de T∗ incorpora la movilidad, las energías de interacción magnética y los coeficientes de difusión térmica (DT) y activo (DA).
Modo de excitación:
Dos fuentes de fluctuaciones, térmicas y activas, actúan de manera diferencial sobre los grados de libertad del sistema, revelando su naturaleza fuera del equilibrio.
Principio clave: rompimiento de la equipartición energética:
En sistemas fuera del equilibrio, las fluctuaciones activas pueden romper la equipartición de energía, especialmente cuando los tiempos de relajación internos del sistema son comparables con el tiempo de persistencia de la fuerza activa (τ).
Esto da lugar a un espectro de temperaturas efectivas específicas para cada modo de relajación, algo que no se había observado experimentalmente en sistemas activos.
Modelo de modos normales:
Las fluctuaciones se analizan en términos de modos normales de relajación en lugar de vibraciones fonónicas tradicionales, ya que las partículas están en un fluido viscoso.
Se define la energía potencial armónica promedio del cristal en función de los desplazamientos (ui) y su transformada de Fourier (uq​) para investigar cómo las fluctuaciones activas afectan las estructuras de los modos.
